04181nam a22005175i 9780674919747DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749197477 a10.4159/97806749197472doi  a(DE-B1597)500404  a(OCoLC)1030304210  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aMUS0350002bisacsh04a306.4/842609731 aStephens, Randall J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Devil’s Music :bHow Christians Inspired, Condemned, and Embraced Rock ’n’ Roll /cRandall J. Stephens. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (330 p.) :b23 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. Pentecostalism and Rock ’n’ Roll in the 1950s -- t2. Race, Religion, and Rock ’n’ Roll -- t3. The Beatles, Christianity, and the Conservative Backlash -- t4. The Advent of Jesus Rock -- t5. The Fundamentalist Reaction to Christian Rock -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen rock ’n’ roll emerged in the 1950s, ministers denounced it from their pulpits and Sunday school teachers warned of the music’s demonic origins. The big beat, said Billy Graham, was “ever working in the world for evil.” Yet by the early 2000s Christian rock had become a billion-dollar industry. The Devil’s Music tells the story of this transformation. Rock’s origins lie in part with the energetic Southern Pentecostal churches where Elvis, Little Richard, James Brown, and other pioneers of the genre worshipped as children. Randall J. Stephens shows that the music, styles, and ideas of tongue-speaking churches powerfully influenced these early performers. As rock ’n’ roll’s popularity grew, white preachers tried to distance their flock from this “blasphemous jungle music,” with little success. By the 1960s, Christian leaders feared the Beatles really were more popular than Jesus, as John Lennon claimed. Stephens argues that in the early days of rock ’n’ roll, faith served as a vehicle for whites’ racial fears. A decade later, evangelical Christians were at odds with the counterculture and the antiwar movement. By associating the music of blacks and hippies with godlessness, believers used their faith to justify racism and conservative politics. But in a reversal of strategy in the early 1970s, the same evangelicals embraced Christian rock as a way to express Jesus’s message within their own religious community and project it into a secular world. In Stephens’s compelling narrative, the result was a powerful fusion of conservatism and popular culture whose effects are still felt today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChristian rock musiczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aFundamentalismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRock musicxHistory and criticism. 0aRock musicxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aRock musiczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Rock.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674919747423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674919747.jpg  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles